  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reply to Park Japddan Inseok's Letter
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to you with reverence. Your letter of the fifth of this month has brought me joy, for it assured me of your good health and peaceful days—a comfort to my long-held concern. The stirrups and military boots you sent to Kim Yuchyeong, I have received in full and already dispatched through my sister's household. She is preparing for her own journey to Yuchyeong these days, so they will surely travel with her.

    Though I received your kind summons, circumstances prevented me from attending you promptly. Shortly after, I learned of your brother's passing into mourning, yet I failed to offer my condolences—a grave breach of human decency. Though I deserve ten thousand deaths for such negligence, I accept this judgment willingly.

    I have long been cast aside by this bright world. Looking back, I see only my own dullness and carelessness, which have drawn the world's coldness upon me. I have shuttered my gate and kept to my humble path, my heart untouched by the courtesies of society—by calls to visit, by inquiries of health—for many years now. I beg your forgiveness for this withdrawal. A small affliction troubles me presently, which only deepens my reluctance to venture out. When it passes, I shall come to your gate bearing thorns of shame to ask your pardon.

    Your mourning period will soon conclude, I trust. I only hope you cherish yourself in these times, that worry may not waste away your frame. I have said all I can say. With utmost respect, I bow my head.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The letter is written in the formal epistolary style typical of Goryeo literati, with the author adopting a humble persona despite being a prominent scholar and official.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'stirrups and military boots' suggests the recipient held a military or official position.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'mourning period' (bokjae) refers to the Confucian ritual observance following a family member's death, typically lasting several years depending on the relationship.
